f history-writings that have strongly influenced Russians’ views of themselves and their past. Through new readings of his drama, Boris Godunov; such narrative poems as Poltava, The Bronze Horseman, and Count Nulin; prose fiction, including The Captain’s Daughter and Blackamoor of Peter the Great; lyrical poems; and a variety of nonfictional texts, the author presents Pushkin not only as a progenitor of Russian national mythology but also as an original historical and political thinker.Evdokimova considers Pushkin within the context of Romantic historiography and addresses the tension between Pushkin the historian and Pushkin the fiction writer . She also discusses Pushkin’s ideas on the complex relations between chance and necessity in historical processes, on the particular significance of great individuals in Russian history, and on historical truth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHistory in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030007023140uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014414740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300144147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300144147/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY